column17: MN AIRLINES LLC D/B/A SUN COUNTRY AIRLINES
column25: UNIVERSITY OF NORTHERN IOWA FOOTBALL TEAM
column168: Sun Country Airlines operated a private charter flight for the University of Northern Iowa football team.  The flight originated out of Waterloo Regional Airport (ALO) with the ground handling of Livingston Aviation.  The ground handlers failed to recognise 2 heaters that were loaded and considered hazardous material.  There were a total of 4 heaters, 2 of which were unused and not considered hazardous material in their original package.  The other 2 heaters had been used and filled with kerosene.  The aircraft then flew without the knowledge of the heaters being in the cargo hold.  At the point in which the equipment for the football team was unloaded the ground handlers at Missoula International Airport/Johnson-Bell Field noticed that there was kerosene fuel that had leaked out of one of the heaters.  The ground handler for Sun Country Airlines at the time of unloading for this flight was North Star Express.  Sun Country Airlines mechanic was then informed about the incident. The mechanic then notified Sun Country Airlines maintenance control and advised the mechanic on what to do with the proper procedures that Sun Country Airlines has in place for a liquid flammable spill.  The mechanic then cleaned the spill up that was contained in the cargo hold of the aircraft per Sun Country Airlines and Boeing task card procedures.  The aircraft was inspected for damage and released for a ferry flight back to MSP where it underwent further inspection.  Upon initial investigation, the company has determined that the vendor for ground handling in ALO failed to detect that they loaded undeclared DG/HAZ onto the aircraft.  No employee working the flight was made aware of the heaters on board prior to landing in MSO.  A full investigation into the matter has been launched and a VDRP has also been filed with the MSP local FSDO.  Please contact Heidi De Hoogh as documented below for additional information as our investigation continues.
column169: Sun Country Airlines shall complete a full investigation into the matter that includes comprehensive fixes and followup audits regarding this incident.  At a minimum, employees will be trained and counseled.  New procedures and processes will be enhanced for vendor communication, training and working with brokers for private charters.  A full report will be available once the investigation is completed by contacting Heidi De Hoogh.

The spill was cleaned up using an absorbent cleaning compound, and the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container, along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill.  The drum was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column63: DOT non coded wet/dry Vacuum truck
column168: A wet/dry vacuum truck operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was cleaning a manhole of debris in Boston MA, upon completion the driver shut down the vacuum and the tanker began to leak. The driver reapplied vacuum stopping the leak and proceeded to vacuum up the product that spilled on the road and manhole. The driver manually closed the hydrulic valve/flange realizing the hydraulic valve had failed securing the load for transportation to the Clean Harbors disposal facility in Braintree MA.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re instructed to insure  that a comprehensive inspection of wet/dry vacuum unit along with the closure device to identify any potential issues prior to transportation. In addition, this  specific vehicle was placed out of service and the hydraulic control box was replaced with a new control by the local Clean Harbors mechanic. The Mass DEP was notified at the time of the spill (Report NE-11-7055)and did not respond satisfied the spill was cleaned up immediatly by the Clean Harbors driver and crew.

column168: During a routine load check, a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was found to have a leaking container.  A response crew was summoned, when they arrived donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A 5 gallon container had tipped on its site against the trailer wall and leaked approximately 1 pint of liquid onto the floor.  The spill was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material and the container overpacked into a salvage container, along with a shovelful of gravel that had been stained under the trailer.  The trailer was then dispatched back to Cincinnati so that the load could be reworked and secured properly.  State of Indiana was notified and assigned incident number 26129 to the file, which they closed immediately due to the small amount leaked and the fact that it was already cleaned up.
column169: The contents of the load were found to be improperly blocked and braced.  This caused the contents to shift and the small items to tip over.  The load went 50 miles back to the origin to be reworked and properly secured.  The loading personnel were instructed to use better care when loading trailers.

column168: On December 15, 2011, a tote containing UN1993 Flammable Liquids N.O.S.,3, PG II, (Methanol, Petroleum Solvents) suffered structural damage to the body of the container resulting in the release of approximately 3 gallons of product onto the floor of the trailer. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. Granular absorbents were applied to the trailer floor and the other cargo onboard was wiped down. The remaining product in the damaged container was transferred into a replacement tote. All waste was then collected and containerized for disposal.

A van trailer returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility after having made multiple pickups of hazardous waste.  While at the gate, it was noticed that liquid was leaking out of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum had leaked its entire contents onto the floor of the trailer.  A suitable cleaning compound and absorbent were used to clean the trailer and the ground beneath it.  The drum and cleanup materials were placed into a suitable salvage container.  A sweeper was obtained to clean the parking lot and the street outside.  The State of Illinois IEPA was notified and assigned incident number H2011-1346 to the case.  The trailer was returned to service and the shipment continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted a narrow steady stream of product leaking from the bottom outlet valve of tank car GATX 4557 (Load: Bisulfites, Aqueous Solutions, N.O.S. - Sodium Bisulfite) while inspecting rail cars at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated in place. CN's response team responded noting the seal intact on the bottom outlet valve handle and liquid coming from the valve. The butterfly type valve handle was not secured in the closed position and valve plug was less than tool tight allowing product to escape. Valve handle was closed and secured in the closed position and plug was tightened, leak stopped, tank car released for movement.

column168: EE had to make an abrupt stop while transporting a R/O can. Material spilled out from the front of the can. Authorities contacted and spill cleaned up. No injuries, prop damage, or envt impact. Driver was following to close to the vehicle in front of him. EE stated he was traveling approximately 50-75 feet behind the car directly in front of him. EE was approaching a green light at the intersection.  The light turned yellow and he anticipated making it through the light.  The vehicle he was traveling behind stopped at the light. EE had to apply the brakes to avoid a rear end collision.  The abrupt stop caused the material in the roll off can to shift forward breaching the tarp cover and spilling out on to the road. The roll off can contained approximately 20 cubic yard bags of sludge/solid material.  1-2 bags of material spilled between the R/O can and cab with the remaining falling on the ground. Driver called 911 to dispatch police & fire dept. PSC Industrial services division arrived 1 hour after the spill was reported to clean up the spilled material. Authorities closed off the right lane and traffic was directed through the left lane for approx 3 hrs. Spill was cleaned up and all lanes of traffic reopened at 9:45pm and the authorities left the scene. Secondary cleanup continued until 11:30 pm. Eight (8) 55 gallon drums of material were generated in the clean up.    Time Line of Events  6:40pm incident occurred, and driver called his supervisor  Driver calls 911 and police & fire dept are dispatched  PSC industrial services group dispatched (JACA) to clean up site.  EHS regional manager notifies Agencies   The NRC report # is 998143, spoke to Petty Officer Layman at approximately 815pm.   Spoke to the Duty Officer, Ben Russell from the PA DEP at approx 845pm.   Spoke to Charles Fitzsimmons of the EPA @ approx 850pm.  JACA arrives on site at 8:45pm  309 shut down to one lane  9:45pm 309 reopened, Fire & Police leave the scene  Secondary clean up & decontamination of vehicle continued until midnight    No violations or citations issued by the PADEP following an investigation on 12/15/2011 by Alex Page (484)250-5766
column169: Root & Contributing factors summation   An internal investigation of the incident determined that the cause of the incident was driver error. The incident was not the result of an equipment failure. Moving forward internal recommendations have been made to require the generator to use bags that are 6 mil in thickness. Use of a roll off can with a front splash guard. Ultimately, additional defensive driver training will prevent a reoccurrence of any future incidents.    Direct Cause  Driver was following to close to the vehicle in front of him. EE stated he was traveling approximately 50-75 feet behind the car directly in front of him.    Root Cause  EE was approaching a green light at the intersection.  The light turned yellow and he anticipated making it through the light.  The vehicle he was traveling behind stopped at the light. EE had to apply the brakes to avoid a rear end collision.  The abrupt stop caused the material in the roll off can to shift forward breaching the tarp cover and spilling out on to the road.    Contributing Factors   The roll off can contained approximately 20 cubic yard bags of solid material.  The roll off can had a splash guard on the rear of the can.  A can with a front splash guard may have contained the material from shifting and spilling out during an unexpected stop.    Corrective Actions  Completion of two (2) Smith System Training courses.

The trailer was loaded with 31% HCl when it arrived at GE Water at Pico Rivera.  When the driver hooked up the load line to the GE Water tank and started to pressurize the trailer, he noticed product coming out of the dome area discharge tube.  He immediately stopped loading and informed the GE personnel and dispatcher at Univar.  The driver then proceeded to place the absorbant pigs to stop the run of HCL on the ground to a confined area.  Later, the driver climbed to see what caused the incidence on top of the trailer and realize that blow down vent valve was left open. The driver failed to carry out DVRI process in it's entirety.    Univar Yard team from Santa fe Springs helped neutralize with Sodium BiCarbonate and cleaned up the 5 to 7 gal spillage in to a 2 - 5 gallon containers. GE Water management has signed off on the clean-up work that was completed and check the ground with pH paper to make sure it was neutralized.
column169: The driver needs to follow the DVRI process to make sure that all the anciliary valves including blow down valves are closed if are not part of the delivery process.  A blow down valve is typically used to clear the chemical hose of all chemical after a delivery using air.

column168: CDL DRIVER WAS 3 HOURS INTO HIS DOT DAY. STARTED AT 2201 ON 02 DEC 2011, AND LOADED 7703 GALLONS OF HEAVY GAS-OIL INTO CARGO TANK TRAILER IN SANDERSVILLE, MS. DELIVERY WAS TO SAME COMPANY IN TUSCALOOSA, AL. HEADING EAST ON I-20 OUT OF MERIDIAN MS, DRIVER ALLOWED VEHICLE TO DEPART ROADWAY (TO THE LEFT), AND ENTER THE MEDIAN BETWEEN THE E/B AND W/B LANES OF TRAVEL. UPON ENTERING MEDIAN, VEHICLE BECAME UNSTABLE DUE TO TERRAIN SLOPE AND OVERTURNED COMPLETELY. CARGO TANK VENT BOX ON TOP OF TRAILER CONTACTED THE GROUND AND WAS TORN OFF CAUSING A RELEASE OF HEAVY GAS OIL FOR APPROX 2 HOURS UNTIL RESPONDERS ARRIVED. WE WERE ABLE TO DISPATCH ANOTHER TANK TRUCK WITH A PUMP, AND RECLAIM A LARGE PORTION OF THE TRAILER CONTENTS. SAND WAS BROUGHT TO THE SITE AND USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL TO 2' X 75' GRASSY AREA IN THE MEDIAN. NO WATERWAYS OR DRAINAGE WAS IMPACTED.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND SITE WAS REMEDIATED BY US ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OUT OF JACKSON, MS.
column169: AN INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED INTO THIS CRASH: ON-BOARD RECORDING DATA INDICATED SPEED FLUCTUATIONS AND A STABILITY CONTROL EVENT IMMEDIATELY BEFORE THE CRASH.  DRIVER LOGS PRECEDING THE CRASH (8 DAYS) WERE IN COMPLIANCE (WE HAVE ELECTRONIC LOG RECORDERS), AND DRIVER HAD 14+ HOURS OFF DUTY PRIOR TO BEGINNING HIS "DAY" ON THE DEC 02.    WE HAVE CONCLUDED THAT FATIGUE WAS THE NOST SIGNIFICANT FACTOR IN THIS CRASH.    WE WILL CONTINUE TO STRESS TO OUR DOT DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF "SLEEP HYGIENE", THAT IS THE IMPORTANCE OF USING THEIR ALLOTTED TIME OFF DUTY TO OBTAIN QUIET, RESTFUL AND RESTORATIVE SLEEP.    I RECOMMEND THAT ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS IN LIQUID CARGO TANKS REQUIRE THE CARGO TANK TO HAVE THE SAME ROLL-OVER PROTECTION REQUIRED OF SPECIFICATION TANKS REGARDLESS OF PACKING GROUP.

wHEN DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOAD IN cINCINNATI OH HE NOTICED THAT THE DRUM HAD BEEN BENT BUT THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE OR SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER SECURED THE LOAD WITH STRAPS AND LOAD LOCKS.  WHEN HE STOPPED FOR A BREAK HE CHECKED HIS LOAD AND NOTICED NO PROBLEMS - THIS WAS A WALK AROUND CHECK.  AFTER HAVING LUNCH HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK AND BEFORE LEAVING HE OPENED THE DOORS TO VERIFY THAT HIS SECUREMENT DEVICES HAD NOT MOVED OR THE LAOD HAD NOT SHIFTED.  HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS LIGUID SEEPING OUT OF SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM THAT HAD BEEN DENTED WHEN IT WAS LOADED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND AROUND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HE ALSO MADE A PATCH TO COVER THE OLE ON THE DRUM.
column169: i INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER THAT WHEN HE NOTICED THE DRUM WAS BENT WHILE AT THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY HE SHOULD HAVE HAD THE DRUM OVERPACKED TO PREVENT ANY POSSIBLE LEAKAGE WHILE THE MATERIAL WAS IN TRANSIT.  I EXPLAINED THAT EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAK AT THE TIME, THAT WITH THE DRUM BEING DAMAMGED HE SHOULD HAVE TAKEN EXTRA PRECAUTIONS AND HAD THE SHIPPER OVERPACK THE DRUM BEFORE HE LEFT THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY.  THE TRAINING HE RECEIVED INSTRUCTS HIM TO INSURE ANY DAMAGED PACKAGES OR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE IS TO BE CORRECTED PRIOR TO LEAVING THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER STANDARDS INCLUDES PREVENTION OF LEAKAGE BY INSURING THE INTEGRITY OF PACKAGES BEFORE LOADING THEM ON A TRANSPORT VEHICLE AND IF THERE IS EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE TO A PACKAGE TO TAKE EXTRA STEPS TO OVERPACK PACKAGES OR OTHERWISE INSURE THAT ACTIONS TO PREVENT FURTHER DAMAGE ARE TAKEN.  THE PROCEDURES TO OREVENT THE SPILL WERE IN-PLACE, NEITHER THE DRIVER NOR THE LOADER FOLLOWED THEM.  ADDITIONAL EMPHASIS ON PACKAGE SECUREMENT AND SPILL PREVENTION WILL BE ADDED TO OUR IN-HOUSE TRAINING.

column168: GATX 17718 load of Petroleum Distillate, N.O.S., UN 1268 was discovered leaking from the manway area while crew was switching in PTRA American Yard at approximately 1230 hours on 12/16/2011. The product was contained on the tank car sides and was isolated for response and remediation. After contacting Chemtrec and the shipper US Environmental Service was contacted to inspect the cause and clean the car. USES arrived on scene and discovered two manway bolts that were loose and no gasket applied on the manway.  They installed a new manway gasket, secured the manway bolts and applied a new seal. The car was released at approximately 1600 hours.

column168: Residue covered hopper car NAHX 93904 was noted by carrier personnel with dust being released from the bottom of the car during humping operations.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found approximately 10 pounds of  material had leaked out of NAHX 93904 on the master retarder at DeButts yard, account metal dump hose damaged.  The discharge tube between the B and C hopper chutes became dislodged from the fittings after the master retarder grabbed the car, causing the tube to drop and become lodged in the master retarder spilling approximately 10 pounds of residue material that was left in the tube after being unloaded. Hepaco wrapped the exposed outlet ends to keep any more residual commodity from leaking onto the ground. Visual inspection revealed no obvious defects to pipe to indicate that it was struck by a foreign object. Suspect retaining bolts on the pipe locking ring were loose and when the master retarder grabbed the car to apply a normal brake, the pipe shook loose from the retaining rings and fell into the retarder from the vibration of the car being grabbed which is normal. The dislodged pipe was damaged, car will have to be Home shopped for repair.    All spilled material was recovered and will be returned to the shipper for further handling and disposal.  The loaded move of this car was covered by a hazardous waste manifest, the return residue move which was involved in this release was not moving under a waste manifest due to the limited amount of material remaining in the car.

column168: GATX 17724, UN1268 had been reported to have product on the side of the car by the shipper on Fridsay, 12/16/2011. At that time the car was at BNSF South Yard. BNSF was notified of the potential NAR however the car was delivered to the PTRA and found in North Yard track 30 at approximately 1530 hours on Monday 12/19/2011. The car showed some evidence of a leak from the manway area and was isolated for inspection and remediation. On Tuesday, 12/20/2011 PTRA was given the permission from the shipper to use a local ER comapany to repair and clean the car. M&M Protection inspected the car and found that the manway gasket was not installed prior to shipment thus causing the car to leak when the product shifted during transport. They installed a new gasket, tightened the bolts and sealed the car. They cleaned the product off the sides using microbug solution. The car was released at 1230 hours.

Driver attempted to secure dome after loading without removing gauging devive. Cargo spilled through partially secured dome onto roadway as driver turned off highway onto connecting road. Consignee personnel noticed spill and reported. Spilled cargo was neutralized and washed off roadway.
column169: Modifications were made to portable gauging device to prevent dome closure until device is completely removed from dome opening.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility to be unloaded and reloaded into other trailers destined for various waste disposal facilities.  When the rear doors were opened, it was noticed that one of the 7 pallets of bags containing 5 gallon pails had shifted to one side and was leaking.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The bag was opened and the contents transferred to a suitable salvage container.  The spilled material was confined to the trailer floor and was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material.  This material was also placed into the salvage container.  The trailer was returned to service and the shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  The state of Illinois emergency management authority was notified, incident number H2011-1346
column169: The driver should not have picked up this shipment as it was packaged.  The generator was notified as to the incident and improper packing and the driver was retrained on proper container selection.

column168: CTMV was positioned for unloading by driver. Driver proceeded to connect cargo hose to receiving line as instructed by consignee personnel. Connection was 2 inch camlock. Driver opened valves on CTMV and applied compressed air to tranfer cargo. At this point camlock fitting disconnected and cargo sprayed from fitting. Consignee person was sprayed with liquid cargo and was quickly taken to a safety shower. Treatment was first aid. Cargo spill was cleanup by consignee personnel. Camlock connection was reattached and secured then unloading proceeded without further incident.
column169: Periodic supervison of unloading reduces this type of incident. Driver was required to secure camlock ears with a restaint before opening valves. This step of the procedure was missed.

column168: THE SUN COUNTRY CHARTER AIRCRAFT N809SY ARRIVED AT 22:13MST AT KMSO. NORTHSTAR JET EMPLOYEES WERE CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE INBOUND ARRIVAL GROUND SERVICES OF THE AIRCRAFT. NORTHSTAR JET EMPLOYEES AT NO TIME WERE INFORMED OF THE PRESENCE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON THE AIRCRAFT. UNLOADING OF PASSENGERS AND CARGO COMMENCED SHORTLY FOLLOWING THE ARRIVAL OF THE AIRCRAFT. THE SPILL WAS DETECTED IN THE REAR CARGO BAY OF THE AIRCRAFT APPROXIMATELY HALFWAY THROUGH THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE. THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL WAS NOT FOUND UNTIL THE LAST COMPARTMENT WAS REACHED. THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL WAS DETERMINED TO BE A KEROSENE FILLED SPACE HEATER THAT HAD BEEN LOADED ON ITS SIDE AGAINST THE REAR BULKHEAD IN REAR BAGGAGE BAY. NORTHSTAR JET EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE AIRCRAFT CREW AT THE FIRST INDICATION OF THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL. NORTHSTAR JET EMPLOYEES INFORMED KMSO PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICERS OF THE KEROSENE SPILL. NORTHSTAR EMPLOYEES WERE NOT GIVEN INSTRUCTION REGARDING THE SPILL. THE CREW SUBSEQUENTLY REQUESTED CLEANUP MATERIALS. UNLOADING OF THE CARGO COMPARTMENTS CONTINUED UNTIL THE BAY WAS EMPTIED. ONCE THE BAY WAS EMPTIED THE SUN COUNTRY MECHANIC ON BOARD THE AIRCRAFT PROCEEDED TO CLEANUP THE SPILL AND INSPECT THE BAGGAGE BAY.

column168: ON 12/27/11 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED AT THE DHL EXPRESS SORT CENTER, 236 WENDELL H FORD BLVD, ERLANGER, KY 41018. INSPECTION OF PACKAGE PRESENTED A PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING 2 PLASTIC BOTTLES AT 250ML EACH. ONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS CRACKED ON THE SIDE AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 75ML. THE BOTTLES WERE MARKED "SEND BACK TO SENDER"; "ALCOHOL, FRAGRANCE"; AND "PRODUCT IS FLAMMABLE UNTIL DRY". TRACKING INDICATES TRANSPORT BY AIR.

THIS WAS A SHIPMENT OF 2 1 ML INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCE VIALS AND 2 KG OF DRY ICE. ALTHOUGH THE SHIPPER USED CLASS 6.2 PACKAGING, THEY MADE INNER PACKAGING ERRORS. THE PACKAGE BURST FROM THE INSIDE OUT - DUE TO THE DRY ICE BEING INSIDE PLASTIC (I SUSPECTED). FEDEX DG SPILL SPECIALISTS DID THE CLEANUP. THE DOT RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED. PETTY OFFICER PALAXXOLA ASSIGNED THIS REPORT # 998147. THE COAST GUARD LATER CALLED TO CONFIRM THAT THE INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCE DID NOT GET INTO A DRAIN. INSTEAD OF JUST CLEARING THE AREA 25' LOCAL MANAGEMENT EVACUTED THE BUILDING OF 65 EMPLOYEES UNTIL IT COULD BE DETERMINED WHAT THE CAUSE OF THE BURST PACKAGE.  UPON DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER THE NEXT DAY - SHE HAD PUT THE DRY ICE INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG. IT WAS UNCLEAR WHETHER OR NOT SHE THOUGHT SHE HAD PUT THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE PLASTIC SECONDARY TUBE OR NOT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL DID NOT GET ON OTHER PACKAGES, EMPLOYEES, OR GET INTO A DRAIN. THE SHIPMENT WAS BE BE HELD THROUGH THE FOLLOWING WEDNESDAY AT THE REQUEST OF DOT/PHMSA. PHOTOS ON THE PACKAGE AFTER IT BURST ARE AVAILABLE.
column169: I SUGGESTED TO THE CUSTOMER THAT THEY WOULD PROBABLY BE SELECTED FOR OUTREACH BY EITHER FAA OR DOT/PHMSA.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, Bosley Oil was struck by a third party, which caused truck to veer off roadway, and rollover into roadside ditch.  Bosley Oil was hauling approximately 7700 gallons of diesel fuel at the time of the accident.  Tank was damaged, resulting in the loss of approximately 5,053 gallons to the roadside ditch, nearby storm drain systems, and connecting retention ponds.  Local Fire Department and Maryland Department of Environment Hazmat Team responded to assess the site, and contain released fuel.  MDE blocked the outlet to the stormwater rentention pond, and contacted FCC Environmental of Baltimore, Maryland to respond to perform the cleanup.  FCC Environnmental responded to recover released fuel and utilized vacuum trucks to recover free liquid from impacted stormwater pond(s).  Heavy rainfall at the time of the incident flushed storm sewer system, and FCC Environmental recovered diesel fuel and water from impacted storm drains, and proceeded to recover residuals from the stormwater retention ponds.  Absorbent boom, stay dry, and absorbent material were used to absorb free product within lot.  FCC Environmental proceeded to recover residuals, and returned the following day to containerize spent absorbent material, and excavate impacted soils.  Filter fencing was put in place to catch residual product, and site was monitored until no contamination remained.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the release.
column169: Bosley Oil will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: After loading approximately 3,000 gallons of material it was noticed that there was material dripping from the noseline dust cap.  The loading process was stopped and the tank was off loaded.  Investigation revealed that there was a defective gasket in the nose line dust cap and that the internal valve was not closing properly. The tank was brought back to the terminal.  Further investigation revealed that the lever between the piston and the internal valve seat was slightly bent, preventing the valve from closing completely.  In addition, the driver had failed to close the gate vale on the nose line and this allowed material to fill the nose line and leak past the dust cap.
column169: Had the driver performed a thorough pre-trip inspection and insured that all the valves were closed there would have not been a leak.  Driver was counseled and retrained on proper pre-trip inspection procedures.

column168: SUMMARY OF EVENTS: EVERGREEN RECYCLING SOLUTIONS, LLC IS A LICENSED SOLID WASTE HAULER AND MATERIAL RECOVERY FACILITY OPERATOR LOCATED IN NEWARK, NJ.  ON DECEMBER 16, 2011, EVERGREEN PURCHASED THE NEW JERSEY HAULING ASSETS OF NACIREMA INDUSTRIES, INC. UNDER A COURT ORDER OF THE NEWARK BANKRUPCY COURT.  THE ORDER ALSO ASSIGNED THE RESPONSIBILITY OF ASSUMING THE EXISTING HAULING CONTRACTS TO EVERGREEN.            EVERGREEN IS NOT LICENSED TO HAUL OR PROCESS HAZARDOUS WASTE NOR DO WE ENGAGE IN THAT BUSINESS.  INADVERTENTLY, ONE  OF THE FORMER NACIREMA SITES, AS SHOWN ABOVE, WE RESPONDED TO A REQUEST FOR PICKUP, NOT KNOWING AHEAD OF TIME THAT THE MATERIAL WAS HAZARDOUS.  OUR DRIVER, WHEN UNCOVERING THIS, BROUGHT THE LOAD TO CLEAN EARTH IN KEARNY, THINKING IT PROPER.  THE NJDEP INSPECTOR LOCATED THE ERROR, AND WE REACTED BY RETURNING THE LOAD BACK TO THE JOBSITE.

column168: It was alleged that the delivery driver was in the process of hooking up a hose to the outlet valve on the IBC.  The driver was standing on a ladder. The IBC was full of the contents (sulfuric acid) and the product came out of the valve.  The delivery driver climbed onto the delivery vehicle and closed the valve.  Driver had on some personal protective equipment, but came into contact with material on several parts of his body.  There was no additional leakage from the IBC or valve once the valve was closed.  There was no packaging failure.

column168: On December 14, 2011 during the inspection of cargo as per instructed from the customer, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed that the container FSCU 654494-7 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 3077 Environmentally hazardous substances, solid, N.O.S.). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.   The container was immediately placed on HOLD status and was prohibited from any future movements. The shipper was advised of the findings and was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On December 16, 2011 upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

column168: HAZMAT SPILL - WORLD AIRWAYS DECEMBER 8, 2011.                                        A 55-GAL DRUM OF UN3082 PETROLEUM NAPHTHA SPILLED INSIDE THE CARGO BIN OF WORLD AIRWAYS AIRCRAFT N275WA ON DECEMBER 8, 2011 IN OSTENDE BELGIUM AT THE OSTENDE-BRUGES INTERNATIONAL (OST) AIRPORT.  THE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED DURING UNLOADING OF CARGO BIN AT 17:26Z.                                                                                                         THE LOCAL FIRE BRIGADES AT OST AIRPORT RESPONDED FOR IMMEDIATE CONTAINMENT WITH WASTE ABSORBENTS.  SMETJET INDUSTRIAL CLEANING WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEANUP OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE ABSORBENT.  THE TASK WAS COMPLETED APPROXIMATELY 14:00 Z, DECEMBER 9, 2011.                                                TOTAL COST OF CLEANUP IS YET TO BE DETERMINED (TBD).

column168: On 12/15/2011, BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Material was informed by the shipper of CRDX 6046 (AAR C314, four compartment covered hopper) that they were notified by consignee that CRDX 6046 arrived at consignee's location missing commodity from hopper compartments with spillage on the ground at their facility. BNSF investigation of car movement records of CRDX 6046 revealed that in transit CRDX 6046 was stopped in Dilworth, MN on 11/17/2011 with a bottom outlet mechanical problem. Local mechanical responders reportedly wired closed a partially open bottom hopper outlet on 11/21/2011. A small amount of product spillage under CRDX 6046 was shoveled, followed by local disposal.   After the aforementioned 12/15/2011 notification, a response contractor was requested to have a vacuum truck go to Dilworth railyard and locations entering the railyard to vacuum up any product spillage found (later reporting that an estimated 3000 lbs. was vacuumed). This captured material was earmarked for appropriate disposal. Also, BNSF mechanical personnel were requested to inspect CRDX 6046 at its Decker, MT location and report on the operation of its bottom outlets. Inspection revealed that number 1 and 4 bottom outlet door gate systems would not close properly to securely lock shut due to capstans needing replacement and door gates out of adjustment.  CRDX 6046 was directed to a repair facility after the consignee unloaded and released it.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of bottom outlet door gate systems.
column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column168: At 2:45am on December 7,2011 Grand Junction Baker Hughes (BHI) was returning a float back to the facility from an oilfield location outside of Parachute CO.  The float was carrying 16 totes of product name Alpha 1427 residue.  The trailer was covered with a tarp designed for the sides to lift up by straps secured over the top rail. During travel one of these straps had been wrapped around a tote valve an worked itself loose and went underneath the rear tires of the trailer and broke the valve off.  This left a trail of liquid approximately 3 miles on the north side of the westbound lane of I-70.  Unit stopped at mm38 after being flagged by another employee.Driver immediately called authorities and local Baker Hughes Management.  Interstate 70 was never closed down. CO DOT provided barriers daily for clean up crews to work in a safe zone. Barriers and signs were used to notify drivers to slow down and travel only in the left hand lane westbound for 3.5 miles.    Clean up was coordinated between Baker Hughes, CURA and CO DOT.  CURA Emergency Services contracted a local company ECOS Enviromental & Disaster Restoration to clean up the spill.  ECOS used scrubbers with suction to wash the pavement.  ECOS will be responsible for the disposal of Fluids pick up.
column169: Employees were re-trained on identifying hazards with using tarp systems on trailers. Design of cover was change so that the straps were always hooked to themselves during transit.

column168: On December 15, 2011, a Landair Transport tractor trailer carrying a 300 gallon tote of UN3109 Corrossive Organic Peroxide had an apparent load shift, which resulted in approximately 110 gallons of material onto the asphalt parking lot. There were ten 300 gallon totes of this material on the trailer and it was reported that the neck of the tote was damaged due to a load shift. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to cleanup the released material. After further investigation the environmental contractor determined that the load shift was due to improper preparation for transport. The environmental contractor collected the released material and containerized all of the waste for transportation and disposal. All of the undamaged totes of material were off loaded and left at the facility. The environmental contractor also cleaned up the impacted trailer floor.
While off-loading product the hose burst and released product.

A pan am railways employye place a rag into the crack to stop the spill.

column168: A BAG CONTAINING 7 PACKAGES ARRIVED IN FEEDER DOOR 36 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:46AM ON 12/15/2011.  LOADER, AISHA WEST, LIFTED BAG FROM ROLLERS TO SCAN AND LOAD IN WALL.  A LIQUID LEAKED FROM BAG AND BEGAN BURNING LOADERS UPPER RIGHT LEG.  EMPLOYEE CONTACTED SUPERVISOR, AND WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO FLUSH AREA.  AREA WAS SECURED BY SUPERVISOR AND RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED OF LIQUID LEAKER.  TIMOTHY POUNDS RESPONDED TO DAMAGE AND PROCEEDED TO TEST PH LEVEL.  PH LEVEL WAS THE HIGHEST ON THE SCALE LEADING TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  RESPONDER FOLLOWED CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  FULL-TIME RMP FOUND PHENOL MSDS BASED UPON INFORMATION PROVIDED BY THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER.  MSDS INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT POISON CONTROL.  POISON CONTROL PROVIDED INFORMATION, AND RECOMMENDED TAKING EXPOSED EMPLOYEE TO HOSPITAL.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE MSDS RMP DISCOVERED PHENOL IS A TOXIC 6 PROHIBITED HAZMAT.  RMP FOLLOWED CHAIN OF COMMAND, CONTACTED P.E., AND DISTRICT SPILL COORDINATOR.  AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED.
column169: SHIPPER FOLLOWUP.

column168: On 12/24/2011 at 1417 hours personnel at the CSXT Queensgate Terminal in Cincinnati, OH discovered GATX 90975, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide, Solution, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Ashta Chemicals, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-12-24-00025. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a faulty vacuum relief device mounted on top of the manway. SWS personnel placed a protective covering over the device and decontaminated the tank car. The shipper's representative, Margrett Coots - 440-997-6815 / 440-813-4826, was informed of the source of the leak and arranged for replacement and requalification.     On December 30, 2011 Rescar, SWS Environmental, and CSXT personnel returned to the site to replace the vacuum relief device and requalify the tank car. GATX 90975 was then released from hold status and placed back into transportation.    This incident did require a special switching move. column168: Vernon White, a delivery specialist at the Geismar #308 location, was making a delivery of HCL 35% to the Wr Grace facility in Lake Charles.  Vernon hooked up the trailer and began to pressure the trailer when a WR Grace unloading operator noticed a drip coming from the sump.  Everything was shut down.  It was determnined that the sump had a hole in it and was dripping HCL through it and onto the unloading rack ground.  The drip was washed to the WR Grace sump and rubber band was placed over the hole and secured with ties.  The leak stopped.  The trailer was later offloaded successfully and was sent immediatly to the cleaning rack.  The trailer was sent to the shop for repairs.  The repairs were completed and the trailer is back in service.
column169: As noted in the initial report, the tank was within a current, specified HM183 test interval. As the trailer was in dedicated service for HCL, material is loaded  on a "closed system" basis. This closed system loading process as well as the nature of the product make internal pre loading inspection difficult to not possible. There was no leakage at the time of loading the cargo tank that was noted.   Post mortem inspection of the cargo tank by the repair facility confirmed that a lining breach in the outer visible failure area of the sump was the root cause of incident. The exact cause of the lining failure is not known at this time however may be possibly  attributed to a disbonding of the lining system with the metal in the area of the sump that occurred over time, or simply a pinhole in the original lining system that existed from the time of the lining application.

column168: NARRATIVE:   While in the process of transferring a load of Toluene the meter on the equipment (Chemex1) stopped counting. The loader shut down the load and called for the manager. After assessing the situation, the level in the trailer was checked. The high level Scully shutdown was retested twice to ensure it was working properly. The Scully probe was checked to ensure it was set for the proper gallon amount to prevent overload. After this TM started the load back up and attempted to get the meter working using the Scully as a fail safe. During this process the Scully shut down failed and material started coming out of the dome of the trailer. A code yellow was announced and loaders responded to the area with spill response equipment. Sand was applied to the area and cleaned up and placed in a container for disposal. No drains or soil were impacted. Material was contained on the asphalt.
column169: ROOT CAUSE:  Metered pump failed to operate properly.    CORRECTIVE ACTION:  Metered pump (Chemex1) has been removed from service pending troubleshooting and repair by manufacturer.

VARIOUS FIRE DEPTS., THE LOCAL EMERGENCY MGMT AGENCY, DEP AND PENN DOTT ASSISTED ON THE SCENE.

column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Claim No. 32413    A cleanup contractor perform cleanup activities at the site under the direction of the Indiana Department of Environmental Management (IDEM).    A vacuum truck was utilized to collect the free product in the road and side of road and the contractor performed diking in the ditchline approximately 1/4 mile from the spill site to contain the release and prevent it from entering waterways.     The contractor utilized 3 vacuum trucks to collect free product from collection trenches surrounding the spill site where the acetone was migrating.    The contractor stabilized an secured the site with the use of the collection trenches and containment dikes. The contractor excavated the contaminated soil in the ditchline.    Final site excavation & restoration activities are being scheduled for completion.

column168: After off loading sulfuric acid into a fixed storage tank at our facility, the delivery personnel attempted to blow out the residual material trapped in the hose. However, the digital level indication did not match up with the level float and the off load was being managed using only the digital level indication. The off load was stopped at 95% on the digital level gauge while the level in the tank was actually near hydraulic. When the off loading line was blown out it caused a small release of acid out the tank overflow line which resulted in a small spill to the paved area around the tank.The off loading line was immediately isolated and actions were taken to contain spill. The estimated quantity that was released is 57 gallons and of that, an estimated 3-5 gallons reached a nearby process sewer before being dammed off for recovery. The material spilled on the pavement was soaked up with sand/gravel and Oil Dri, and placed in a container, where it was later neutralized, prior to disposal.
column169: We have made the following changes in our procedures to ensure this type of incident does not happen: Train operators to ensure that both level gauges are operating correctly before unloading into storage drum.

column168: Before driver left domiciled facility for his daily delivery run he noticed that he had a loose drum loaded on the floor of his trailer. The driver secured the drum to the side of his trailer with a strap and proceeded to his first stop which was the consignee of the drum. Upon arrival the driver opened his back door and observed the drum leaking. The driver immediately unstrapped it from the wall of the trailer and flipped it over noting that the drum was relatively light. The driver noticed that there was a bolt protruding from the floor of the trailer that the drum had been loaded on top of and as a result it consequently punctured the bottom of the drum resulting in the unintentional release. For as much of the contents that released there was very little to clean up because the spilled material evaporated rather quickly. The consignee kept the damaged drum.
column169: Loaders need to pay attention and visually inspect the floor of the trailer to prevent these kinds of events from occurring.

column168: Driver was proceeding to a propane delivery on a gravel road at a hairpin turn. He stopped the truck because he lost momentum. The truck began to slide sideways and over the bank, dislodging the hose reel and severing the rubber hose between the piping and the hose reel, expelling product for approximately 30 seconds. Automatic redundant fail-safe protection systems activated, minimizing the release to only the propane in the delivery hose. The release was stopped prior to the driver exiting the cab. The driver received only minor injuries; was transported to the hospital, treated and released.

column168: THE INCIDENT INVOLVED A SINGLE COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT, WITH ONE INJURY, (THE INCIDENT DRIVER), ONE TOWED VEHICLE (THE INCIDENT VEHICLE), THE CLOSURE OF A PUBLIC ROAD, AND THE SPILLAGE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.                                             WHEN TRAVELING AT 53 MPH ON A NARROW, RURAL, TWO-LANE PAVED ROADWAY, THE VEHICLE WENT OFF THE ROADWAY, STRADDLING THE FOG LINE WITH ITS PASSENGER SIDE TIRES ON A 2-FT WIDE, PAVED CONCRETE SHOULDER SPECIFICALLY BUILT TO PREVENT A WASHOUT OF THE ROADWAY.  THE DRIVER LET OFF ON THE THROTTLE, TRAVELED ABOUT 100 FT, THEN HARD-BRAKED LEAVING ABS SKID MARKS.  THE DRIVER STEERED THE VEHICLE TO THE LEFT TO RETURN TO THE ROADWAY, BUT WENT TOWARDS THE OPPOSING LANE, WHEREIN DRIVER OVERSTEERED TO THE RIGHT CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO ROLL ON ITS DRIVER SIDE.  THERE WAS A SPILL OF 6,600 POUNDS OF CLASS 5, DIVISION 5.1 MATERIAL.                                                                                                         THE DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS CARRIER OF THE INCIDENT.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE CARRIER NOTIFIED ITS SPILL RESPONDER SERVICE OF THE INCIDENT AND THEY DISPATCHED A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN-UP SERVICES.  CARRIER EMPLOYEES, OPERATING OTHER VEHICLES IN THE VICINTY OF THE INCIDENT VEHICLE, WENT TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED FIRST RESPONDERS IN RECOVERY EFFORTS.                                         THERE WERE NO WITNESSES TO THIS INCIDENT, OTHER THAN THE DRIVER OF THE INCIDENT VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER STATED HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO AVOID A POTENTIAL COLLISION WITH AN ON-COMING VEHICLE WHEN HE PURPOSELY TOOK EVASIVE ACTION.  A CRASH RECONSTRUCTION EXPERT, HIRED BY THE CARRIER, WAS ON SCENE THE DAY FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT.  THE EXPERT CONTENDS THAT THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS DUE TO DRIVER INATTENTION.
column169: THE CARRIER WILL:                                                                                                   1) REVIEW ITS SMITH DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM FOR SPECIAL PERMIT VEHICLES TO ENSURE THAT IT IS SUFFICIENT TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF ROLLOVER INCIDENT.                              2) REPORT THE INCIDENT CONDITIONS, FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS TO ALL MANAGERS RESPONSIBLE FOR TRANSPORTATION, WHO MAY SHARE IT WITH COMPANY DRIVERS WHOM THEY SUPERVISE.

column168: coop employee was loading fuel truck with dyed diesel when the bulk tank ran out of fuel.  the new shipment of dyed diesel arrived and the employee went to help the driver hook up lines to unload into bulk tank. the coop employee forgot to turn of the valve going to the bulk truck so when the tanker truck started pumping fuel off his truck into bulk tank the fuel was going into the bulk delivery truck filling it up and then began to run over.  the coop employee noticed this as he returned to the truck and began turning off the valve he had left on stopping the flow of fuel to the truck. the coop employee then informed me of the spill and i began immediate actions to contain the spill so that it could be cleaned up.we successufully recovered about 200 gallons of diesel and dug up the area and properly disposed of the materials as instructed by Griggs and Maloney,they also did site testing on the area of the spill which came back testing good free of contaminents. the duration of release was less than one minute. the liquid was cleaned up in about two hours

column168: A Highlands Fuel Delivery LPG 6 wheel tanker truck was traveling on Daniel Plummer Road in Goffstown, NH. The truck was traveling down a slight grade and entering a slight left hand turn. The truck encountered black ice conditions on the road and began to loose control. The truck slid sideways and then rolled over. The piping leading to the meter device on the truck became loose and began releasing vapor. Both police and fire responded to the location as did LP Technicians from Highlands Fuel Delivery. The leak was controled in aprox. 45 mins and then the long process of pumping off the remaining product from the truck was started. The truck was then recovered back onto its tires, the remaining product was pumped off and the truck was towed from the location. There were no citations issued to the driver as a result of this accident.
column169: Based on the road conditions on this morning it was determined that the accident was unavoidable as the roads had not been treated with salt or sand prior to the accident.

ON 12-9-2011 AT 5AM WE GOT TO UPSTATE SHREDDER IN OWEGO NY TO FILL THE EQUIPMENT AND 500 GALLON TANK. WHILE FILLING THE TANK OUR DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED BY AN EMPLOYEE THERE AND LEFT THE NOZZLE TO TALK TO HIM. WHY I CAN'T TELL YOU. THEY ARE TRAINED NEVER LEAVE THE NOZZLE IF YOU ARE PUMPING OIL.  THE GAUGE BLEW OFF THE TANK SPEWING OIL OUT. THE DRIVER CONTACTED MYSELF & I CALLED GARY DYER EXCAVATING TO RESPOND FOR CLEAN-UP, THEY ARE 20 MINUTES FROM THE SPILL. I THEN CALLED DEC 800# TO REPORT THE SPILL & MY DIRECT SUPERVISOR.  WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE SITE DEC WAS ALREADY THERE & 50% OF THE CLEAN-UP DONE. LUCKILY THE OIL WAS CONTAINED IN A PAVED CLUVENT SO NO SOIL WAS AFFECTED.  I HAVE ATTACHED A LETTER FROM GARY DYER REGARDING THE QUANTITY. THE TANK OTHER THAN THE GAUGE WAS NOT COMPROMISED.
column169: I SAT DOWN WITH MY 2 SENIOR DRIVERS TO MAKE SURE HIS TRAINING COVERED WHAT HAD HAPPENDED. AND NOT LEAVING THE NOZZLE WAS COVERED BY BOTH NUMEROUS TIMES IN TRAINING. IN 27 YEARS I HAVE NOT HAD THIS PROBLEM, HOWEVER EVEN THOUGH IT WAS A COSTLY CLEAN-UP AND FINE IT DOES SERVE AS A LEARNING TOOL. THE DRIVERS COULD SEE FIRST HAND THE DAMAGE AND COST INVOLVED IN STRAYING FROM OUR SAFETY RULES WE HAVE IN PLACE. TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE I CAN ONLY SAY THAT CONSTENT REMINDING THE DRIVERS AND MEETING WITH THEM ON AN INDIVIDUAL BASIS IS MY PLAN.

column168: Verdegaal Brothers, Inc. company driver was driving a combination rig, Truck 23, which had a cargo tank, and a pull trailer with a cargo tank, transporting a load of 93% sulfuric acid. Driver was west­ bound on State Highway 198, just west of the town of Coalinga, in Fresno County. The driver looked in the mirror and saw his pull trailer leaning to the right, as he came to a curve going to the left. The trailer kept leaning to the right. The trailer went all the way over, onto its side. A few seconds later, the truck starting leaning to the right too. Truck 23 also laid over on the right side.    There never was a leak from the liquid load in the pull trailer cargo tank.    700 pounds  or 45½  gallons of sulfuric acid leaked from the truck cargo tank. This was determined by re-weighing the load, following the incident, in Truck 22 at Verdegaal Brothers' truck scale.    When Verdegaal Brothers' HazMat responders arrived at the scene with a vacuum tanker, the crew connected a hose to vacuum the sulfuric acid from the three-inch bottom outlet, which was towards the top of the overturned vehicle. The sulfuric acid was to be vacuumed into Truck 22, which was also a vacuum tanker.   With the responders created a vacuum from Tank 22, sulfuric acid did not transfer.  The sulfuric acid liquid level was below the level of the three-inch bottom outlet, because the truck was on its side.    There is a ball in a cage in a canister at the front of the cargo tank. This is designed to prevent the cargo tank from being overfilled. When the three-inch valve and cam lock at the rear was opened, in the first attempt to vacuum the contents, the cargo? Tank was vented to ambient pressure. Vacuum was started from another truck, to remove the sulfuric acid from the cargo tank. When the vacuum was started, the ball was no longer in position at the top of the cage and sulfuric acid started to siphon out through the canister and bottom hose to the ground.  When this started to occur, Verdegaal Brothers responders shut off the air valve on the green three-inch line. The toggle switch on the air line, which opens the top valve, was at the open position. This was not initially noticed because the switch was on the side of the truck lying on the ground. With closing the air switch and valve, sulfuric acid stopped siphoning out and no additional acid was released.    With the help of two tow trucks, the pull trailer, still with its load of sulfuric acid, was unhitched and pulled upright. The sulfuric acid in the trailer was transferred into Truck 22. Truck 23 was righted on its axles after the sulfuric acid was vacuumed out of the cargo tank. Truck 23 was towed to Verdegaal Brothers' yard in Hanford. The driver was not injured.  State Highway 198 was partially closed to traffic from approximately 10 AM to 6 PM.
column169: The air actuation switches have since been reversed, to where the off position is to the rear. It was not considered when the switches were mounted that the truck would tip over,and the forward momentum would cause the switch to flip to the open position.  By reversing the switch,it is less likely to open if the cargo tank is on its side and moving forward.  The switch is also spring loaded with pressure to keep it in the closed position.    Drivers are currently instructed if there is a problem, break the air line from the switch to the valve, with a pair of dykes or a knife,or pull it off with their hand, and the lack of air pressure will prevent the air vent on top from opening.    Drivers have since been instructed that is forbidden for loaded company trucks to travel on State Highway 198 between Coalinga and San Lucas.    Verdegaal Brothers drivers have subsequently received four hours of truck driver simulator training at College of Sequoias, on driving skills.

column168: AN IRVING ENERGY LPG DELIVERY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON RT 100B IN MOORETOWN, VT. A PASSENGER CAR TRAVELING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION CROSSED THE CENTER LINE OF THE ROAD INTO THE PATH OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK ATTEMPTED TO AVOID THE ON-COMING CAR BY MOVING INTO THE BREAKDOWN LANE UP AGAINST THE GUARD RAIL. THE PASSENGER CAR STRUCK THE PROPANE TRUCK CAUSING A GAUGE TO BE BROKEN OFF THE SIDE OF THE TANK. THE TRUCK CAME TO REST IN THE DITCH ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROAD. BOTH THE TRUCK AND THE PASSENGER CAR WERE A TOTAL LOSS. THE THREE PASSENGERS IN THE CAR DIED AS A RESULT OF THE CRASH.  THE VERMONT STATE POLICE AND LOCAL MOORETOWN FIRE/RESCUE RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT ALONG WITH TECHNICIANS FROM IRVING ENERGY.  THE PROPANE TRUCK WAS EMPTY AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT AND WAS RETURNING TO RE-LOAD.  THE CARGO TANK HAD VAPOR AND RESIDUE ONLY.  THE REMAINING RESIDUE AND VAPOR WAS BURNED OFF USING A CONTROL STICK PRIOR TO BEING TOWED FROM THE ACCIDENT LOCATION.
